line=59 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=310.44,427.04,468.75,441.02 iscore=0.00                :                                           telic                atelic
line=60 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0,F3-14.0 bbox=116.88,403.75,501.57,418.76 iscore=0.10:          inherent  agentive         λy λx λs [ACT(x)      λy λx λs [ACT(x)
line=61 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=116.88,387.61,491.44,402.14 iscore=0.20        :          control   non-agentive       & DIE(y)](s)         &  BOIL(y)](s)
line=62 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,364.04,538.63,378.02 iscore=0.08                  :Ditransitive verbs nearly always can be decomposed and have  a telic second predic-
line=63 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,347.9,538.6,361.88 iscore=0.15                    :ate. In the ‘give’ type verbs, denoting possession transactions, the second predicate is
line=64 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,331.81,538.6,345.8 iscore=0.08            :BECOME  POSS, while in the ‘speech’ type verbs, denoting communicative transactions,
line=65 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,315.73,273.38,329.72 iscore=0.27          :the second predicate is BECOME KNOW.
line=66 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,293.6,216.98,307.58 iscore=0.17                   :(4)   Ditransitive predicates
line=67 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0,F3-14.0 bbox=90.72,276.49,427.02,290.48 iscore=0.10 :      ‘give’ type:   λz λy λx λs [ACT(x) & BECOME POSS(y,z)](s)
line=68 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0,F3-14.0 bbox=90.72,259.33,434.88,273.32 iscore=0.90 :      ‘speech’ type: λz λy λx λs [ACT(x) & BECOME KNOW(y,z)](s)
line=69 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,237.2,538.65,251.18 iscore=0.14                   :We  are now in the position to define the notions ‘argument hierarchy’ and ‘argument
line=70 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,221.12,538.55,235.1 iscore=0.14                   :linking’ more precisely. Argument hierarchy means that the arguments of a predicate
line=71 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,204.02,538.59,218.0 iscore=0.14                   :are strictly ordered (as shown in the λ−sequences in the examples above), partly in
line=72 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,187.88,538.64,201.86 iscore=0.36                  :virtue of their semantic role (agents are always highest), partly for arbitrary reasons.
line=73 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,171.8,538.64,185.78 iscore=0.38                   :This ordering plays an important role for the morphosyntactic realization of argu-
line=74 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,155.65,538.6,169.64 iscore=0.17           :ments. Even  arguments of semantically symmetric  predicates such as MEET(x,y) are
line=75 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,139.58,538.53,153.56 iscore=0.12                  :ordered; the same is true if such a predicate is part of a ditransitive verb, for instance,
line=76 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0,F2-14.0 bbox=56.7,123.49,406.96,137.48 iscore=0.12  :introduce can be decomposed  as follows: ACT(x) & MEET(y,z).
line=77 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,107.36,538.56,121.34 iscore=0.14                 :   Argument  linking means the way in which the arguments of a predicate are speci-
line=78 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,91.28,538.61,105.26 iscore=0.00                   :fied within a clause by  either morphological  or syntactic means. Morphological
line=79 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,75.2,538.57,89.18 iscore=0.23                     :means  include those that are specified on the head (the predicate expression itself),

