line=81 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,758.18,538.61,772.16                     :such as pronominal affixes, clitics, or agreement morphemes, as well as those that are
line=82 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,742.1,538.58,756.08 iscore=0.07          :specified on the dependent, namely morphological  case on complements.  Argument
line=83 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,726.02,538.61,740.0 iscore=0.20          :linking is syntactic if the argument role is only specified by the position with respect
line=84 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,709.88,121.51,723.86 iscore=0.07         :to the head.
line=85 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,693.8,538.66,707.78 iscore=0.08         :   In the literature, the notion of abstract case has been introduced for determining
line=86 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,677.72,538.65,691.7 iscore=0.08          :the morpho-syntactic realization of arguments. In Lexical Decomposition  Grammar
line=87 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,660.56,538.63,674.54 iscore=0.17         :(LDG),  abstract case is identified with argument hierarchy. The λ-abstractors for ar-
line=88 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,644.48,538.6,658.46 iscore=0.25          :gument  variables constitute the theta-roles; their ordering expresses the argument hi-
line=89 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,628.34,538.59,642.32 iscore=0.20         :erarchy (with the lowest argument to the left and the highest argument to the right).
line=90 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,612.26,538.67,626.24 iscore=0.27         :Abstract case, then, is encoded by means of two  relational features associated with
line=91 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,596.18,445.13,610.16 iscore=0.15         :theta-roles ([+hr] ‘there is a higher role’, [+lr] ‘there is a lower role’).
line=92 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,580.04,538.57,594.02 iscore=0.00        :   In this paper I will show, however, that abstract case is too a specific device for
line=93 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,563.96,538.64,577.94 iscore=0.00         :characterizing argument linking in general. Contrary to what many theorists believe,
line=94 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,547.88,538.72,561.86 iscore=0.14         :there seems to be no universal argument  linking device. I will claim that Universal
line=95 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,531.74,538.61,545.72 iscore=0.14         :Grammar   (UG)  only incorporates the idea of relational predicates whose arguments
line=96 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,515.66,538.65,529.64 iscore=0.07         :are ordered, as well as the semantic factors which can be chosen as the determining
line=97 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,499.58,538.67,513.56 iscore=0.20         :factors. More specifically, I will claim that all argument linking types are invented on
line=98 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,483.5,239.54,497.48 iscore=0.07          :the basis of mainly three factors:
line=99 fonts=F1-14.0,F3-14.0 bbox=74.7,466.64,297.44,480.62 iscore=0.17 :   •  Semantic  roles (agent vs. non-agent)
line=100 fonts=F1-14.0,F3-14.0 bbox=74.7,449.66,216.91,463.64 iscore=0.33:   •  Salience of arguments
line=101 fonts=F1-14.0,F3-14.0 bbox=74.7,432.68,205.77,446.66 iscore=0.50:   •  Argument  hierarchy
line=102 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,409.64,538.55,423.62 iscore=0.05        :A  choice for salience can be made in terms of person (1, 2 > 3), number (sg > pl),
line=103 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,392.66,538.6,406.64 iscore=0.26         :animacy  (+anim > −anim), or specificity (+spec > −spec), however, I will restrict my-
line=104 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,375.68,269.23,389.66 iscore=0.21        :self in this paper to the role of person.
line=105 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,358.64,538.67,372.62 iscore=0.21       :   In general I will not refer to grammatical relations such as ‘subject’ and ‘object’,
line=106 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,341.66,538.59,355.64 iscore=0.21        :except these terms are related to the highest or a non-highest argument, respectively.
line=107 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,324.68,538.59,338.66 iscore=0.15        :Besides for semantic purposes, the term ‘subject’ is also used for morpho-syntactic
line=108 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,307.64,538.62,321.62 iscore=0.25        :purposes: then, ‘subject’ either relates to the nominative argument (morphologically)
line=109 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,290.66,538.57,304.64 iscore=0.13        :or to the argument designated for a syntactic position (such as SpecI). Because of this
line=110 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,273.68,538.61,287.66 iscore=0.20        :ambiguity, an undifferentiated use of ‘subject’ is problematic for typological needs.
line=111 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,256.64,538.61,270.62 iscore=0.14        :The problem  with the term ‘object’ is that the specification ‘direct’ vs. ‘indirect ob-
line=112 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,239.66,538.59,253.64 iscore=0.40        :ject’ often does not meet their grammatical relevance; I will turn to this problem be-
line=113 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,222.68,81.17,236.66 iscore=0.07         :low.
line=114 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,205.64,538.66,219.62 iscore=0.00       :   Let us assume that a grammar  imposes a number  of constraints for the realization
line=115 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,188.66,538.59,202.64 iscore=0.14        :of arguments.  Besides other, quite plausible constraints (such as ‘Mark  person’,
line=116 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,171.68,519.74,185.66 iscore=0.29        :‘Mark  number’), the following seems to be play a crucial role in argument linking:
line=117 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,148.64,367.72,162.62 iscore=0.07        :(5)   Avoid converse settings to be identically marked.
line=118 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,125.66,538.61,139.64 iscore=0.15        :Obviously, this is an important subcase of ‘Avoid ambiguity’. (6) illustrates two of
line=119 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,108.68,538.63,122.66 iscore=0.20        :the settings that are subject to (5), that is, should be expressed differently. In general,

