line=248 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,597.37,538.65,611.36 iscore=0.11                                                         :Prefixes from the AGT set cannot be said to be ergative, and those from the PAT set are
line=249 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,580.4,538.56,594.38 iscore=0.06                                                                  :not accusative, because these prefixes never contrast with an unmarked item nomina-
line=250 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,563.36,538.64,577.34 iscore=0.31                                                                 :tive. Hence, the Salience type is, like the Active type, purely semantically determined
line=251 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,546.38,418.32,560.36 iscore=0.23                                                                 :and should not be confounded with argument linking using case.
line=252 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,529.4,535.18,543.38 iscore=0.07                                                                 :   At the other extreme one can find a purely structural argument linking type, where
line=253 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,512.36,417.24,526.34 iscore=0.21                                                                 :the role of an argument correlates with its position in the syntax.

doc_id=101 page=7 block_id=7-3 bbox=56.7,223.4,538.73,484.4 label=b 254 267
line=254 fonts=F1-14.0,F1-16.0 bbox=56.7,468.38,538.63,484.4      :2.4   Positional  type: The argument  hierarchy is mapped  to syntactic positions,
line=255 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,451.4,538.57,465.38 iscore=0.13  :with the highest argument to the first and the lowest argument to the last position.
line=256 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,434.36,538.73,448.34 iscore=0.13 :This type is also the last resort under other circumstances; for instance, if two argu-
line=257 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,417.38,538.6,431.36 iscore=0.33  :ments bear the same case they usually are distinguished by their position. The map-
line=258 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,400.4,538.61,414.38 iscore=0.18  :ping to syntax is illustrated in (13) for a ditransitive verb of the ‘give’ type. Under the
line=259 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,383.36,538.6,397.34 iscore=0.18  :assumption  that ‘give’ can be decomposed  as shown  in (4), the argument ranking
line=260 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,366.38,538.63,380.36 iscore=0.24 :clearly is x (agent) > y (recipient) > z (theme). In a verbfinal language such as Ger-
line=261 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,349.4,420.2,363.38 iscore=0.35   :man  or Japanese (which both also have case), the default order is
line=262 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,326.36,386.82,340.34 iscore=0.27:   NP-x (nominative) – NP-y (dative) – NP-z (accusative).
line=263 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,303.38,538.59,317.36 iscore=0.12 :In a verbsecond language such as English or Chinese (which do not have case in full
line=264 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,286.4,224.97,300.38 iscore=0.06  :nominals), the default order is
line=265 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,263.36,217.03,277.34 iscore=0.43:   NP-x – V – NP-y  – NP-z,
line=266 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,240.38,538.61,254.36 iscore=0.07 :which is also known as double object construction. Such a construction is also found
line=267 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,223.4,385.63,237.38 iscore=0.21  :in Creole languages and especially in the Bantu languages.

