line=282 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,486.26,538.61,500.24 iscore=0.00                :The argument  hierarchy can be encoded by the features [+hr] ‘there is a higher argu-
line=283 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,469.28,538.59,483.26 iscore=0.20                :ment, and (optionally) [+ho] ‘there is a higher object’; the same features can be used
line=284 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,452.24,538.61,466.22 iscore=0.33                :to specify the positions with respect to the verb: arguments specified as [+hr] are real-
line=285 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,435.26,538.61,449.24 iscore=0.18                :ized to the right of the verb, while the highest argument ([−hr]) is realized to the left
line=286 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,418.28,538.61,432.26 iscore=0.12                :of the verb, possibly in a Spec-position. This enables us to speak of a ‘subject posi-
line=287 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,401.24,538.59,415.22 iscore=0.31                :tion’. [+ho] is a more specific feature, which implies [+hr]; the highest object ([−ho])
line=288 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,384.26,538.64,398.24 iscore=0.12                :usually is realized next to the verb – it is called the ‘primary object’, while all other
line=289 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,367.28,538.6,381.26 iscore=0.24                 :objects are ‘secondary objects’. This terminology  differs from that for case lan-
line=290 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,350.24,499.03,364.22 iscore=0.17                :guages, where the lowest argument is designated as ‘direct object’ (see below).
line=291 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,327.98,536.37,341.96 iscore=0.33                :(14)  Possible features for encoding the positions in the positional type (verbsecond):
