line=308 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,660.92,538.53,674.9                                                                            :As many  researchers have shown  (Bresnan & Moshi  1990, among  others), the Bantu
line=309 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,643.88,538.57,657.86 iscore=0.38                                                               :languages suggest an interesting subtypology of the positional type: some languages
line=310 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,626.9,538.66,640.88 iscore=0.18                                                                :(such as Sesotho, Kichaga, Kinyarwanda, Marathi) exhibit so-called symmetrical ob-
line=311 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,609.92,538.62,623.9 iscore=0.18                                                                :jects, while other languages (such as  Kikuyu, Chichew^a,  Swahili) exhibit asym-
line=312 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,592.88,538.61,606.86 iscore=0.08                                                               :metrical objects. One can capture this difference by the assumption that the former
line=313 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,576.62,508.1,590.6 iscore=0.15                                                                 :subtype lacks the feature [+ho], while the latter subtype conforms to this feature.
line=314 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,559.82,538.51,573.8 iscore=0.14                                                               :   In the symmetrical object languages the positions to the right of V are equally
line=315 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,542.78,538.62,556.76 iscore=0.29                                                               :good  for both objects (only salience plays some role: animates usually precede in-
line=316 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,525.8,502.63,539.78 iscore=0.23                                                                :animates): consider (16), where both distributions allow for two interpretations.
line=317 tag=M+AC+LN+CN span_id=101-9 lang_name=Sesotho lang_code=sot fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,502.82,332.67,516.8 iscore=0.10   :(16)  Symmetrical objects in Sesotho [Lee 2000]
