line=332 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,229.82,538.59,243.8 iscore=0.00                                                                :In contrast, asymmetrical object languages have  a fixed position of their objects,
line=333 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,212.78,538.59,226.76 iscore=0.13                                                               :only depending on  their ranking, and salience does not play any role. Thus, only one
line=334 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,195.8,538.59,209.78 iscore=0.13                                                                :interpretation is possible. This is shown by the following examples from Kikuyu; if
line=335 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,178.82,538.64,192.8 iscore=0.14                                                                :the NPs following the verbs are switched in their position, the interpretation is shifted
line=336 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,161.78,495.11,175.76 iscore=0.43                                                               :too. Thus, Kikuyu conforms to the notion of ‘primary’ vs. ‘secondary object’.
