line=354 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,535.46,538.57,549.44 iscore=0.08                                                             :The majority of asymmetrical object languages (e.g., Chichew^a and Swahili) are non-
line=355 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,518.48,538.69,532.46 iscore=0.27                                                             :alternating in that only the argument next to the verb (the primary object) can become
line=356 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,501.5,538.56,515.48 iscore=0.27                                                              :subject under passive. Note that in the Bantu languages the subject usually is co-
line=357 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,484.46,538.68,498.44 iscore=0.36                                                             :indexed with the verb, and that also object affixes are possible under special circum-
line=358 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,467.48,538.62,481.46 iscore=0.14                                                             :stances; these languages thus have some additional means to support argument link-
line=359 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,450.5,538.56,464.48 iscore=0.15                                                              :ing. There is nothing that reflects direct and inverse settings directly, however, the
line=360 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,433.46,538.6,447.44 iscore=0.13                                                              :existence of passive makes it possible to realize a more salient object in the desig-
line=361 fonts=F1-14.0,F1-9.0 bbox=56.7,416.48,202.02,431.96 iscore=0.07                                                      :nated position of subject.^{2}
line=362 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,399.5,538.62,413.48 iscore=0.00                                                             :   The positional type of argument linking requires a syntax with rather fixed word
line=363 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,382.46,538.63,396.44 iscore=0.08                                                             :order; it does not need morphological means, notwithstanding that languages of this
line=364 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,365.48,538.61,379.46 iscore=0.15                                                             :type often exhibit those means, such as additional subject agreement. Next I discuss
line=365 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,348.5,380.77,362.48 iscore=0.08                                                              :the inverse type, which is only possible with morphology.

doc_id=101 page=10 block_id=10-3 bbox=56.7,72.43,538.69,253.4 label=b 366 379
line=366 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-7.0 bbox=56.7,241.39,538.51,253.4                                                                       :2   Besides sortal salience, also discourse prominence (such as topicality) plays a role in the choice of pas-
line=367 fonts=F1-11.0 bbox=73.68,228.43,538.61,239.41 iscore=0.24                                                                :    sive. Some Bantu languages even allow discourse prominence to play a significant role in argument link-
line=368 fonts=F1-11.0 bbox=73.68,215.41,538.49,226.39 iscore=0.06                                                                :    ing: Under the condition that the semantic roles of the arguments are obvious, the positions of the higher
line=369 fonts=F1-11.0 bbox=73.68,202.39,538.61,213.37 iscore=0.25                                                                :    and lower argument can be reversed if the latter is topic. In such a case, the ‘subject’ agreement on the
line=370 fonts=F1-11.0 bbox=73.68,189.43,538.63,200.41 iscore=0.30                                                                :    verb turns out to be in fact topic agreement. Consider the following examples from Kinyarwanda (Mori-
line=371 fonts=F1-11.0 bbox=73.68,176.41,127.47,187.39 iscore=0.06                                                                :    moto 2000).
line=372 tag=L span_id=101-16 lang_name=Kinyarwanda lang_code=kin fonts=F1-11.0 bbox=73.68,163.39,260.05,174.37 iscore=0.20       :    (i) b. Umuhuungu    ki-som-a   igitabo.
