line=381 fonts=F1-14.0,F1-16.0 bbox=56.7,745.46,538.57,761.48                                                                      :2.5   Inverse type:  Affixes on the verb (the direct or inverse marker, often also
line=382 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,728.48,538.64,742.46 iscore=0.43                                                                  :called ‘voice marker’) encode whether the higher or the lower argument is more sali-
line=383 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,711.5,538.56,725.48 iscore=0.13                                                                   :ent; in other words, these voice markers assign relative salience in the context of ar-
line=384 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,694.46,538.57,708.44 iscore=0.13                                                                  :gument  hierarchy (Wunderlich 1996). Computationally, this is the most complex type
line=385 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,677.48,538.62,691.46 iscore=0.21                                                                  :of argument linking because two hierarchies are mapped onto each other. In its pure
line=386 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,660.5,538.54,674.48 iscore=0.07                                                                   :form, this type is only known from  the Algonquian languages, although there are
line=387 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,643.46,538.59,657.44 iscore=0.29                                                                  :more  languages that have an inverse marker, at least in some of their constructions.
line=388 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,626.48,538.63,640.46 iscore=0.27                                                                  :An illustration is given by the examples in (20) from Plains Cree, which are identical
line=389 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,609.5,382.29,623.48 iscore=0.13                                                                   :except the markers that immediately follow the verb stem.
line=390 tag=M+AC+LN+CN span_id=101-18 lang_name=Plains Cree lang_code=crk fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,587.18,499.19,601.16 iscore=0.17:(20)  Inverse morphology in Plains Cree [Wolfart & Carroll 1981, Fabri 1996]
