line=534 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,228.32,538.62,242.3 iscore=0.00                   :As  already indicated, the generalized case type allows some typological variation:
line=535 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,212.17,538.64,226.16 iscore=0.08          :some  languages exhibit ACC, others ERG, some have an ACC-ERG split; languages that
line=536 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,196.09,538.61,210.08 iscore=0.24          :lack DAT may  vary in respect of how they realize the medial argument, if at all (Stie-
line=537 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,180.01,538.63,194.0 iscore=0.12           :bels 2000a,b). Particularly interesting is the possibility of an ACC or ERG split, which
line=538 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,163.93,538.65,177.92 iscore=0.21          :allows to encode salience. For instance, ACC is often lacking for 3rd person, while
line=539 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,147.79,538.6,161.78 iscore=0.19           :ERG is lacking for 1st and 2nd person (as in Dyirbal, Dixon 1994). Similarly, ERG is
line=540 fonts=F1-11.0,F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,131.71,538.63,145.7 iscore=0.38           :sometimes  restricted to the perfect, while ACC  occurs in  the imperfect (as in
line=541 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,115.64,538.57,129.62 iscore=0.23                  :Hindi/Urdu, Mohanan  1994). I will demonstrate here that the relevant constraints fol-
line=542 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,99.5,538.59,113.48 iscore=0.25                    :low  from the harmonic  alignment of scales (Prince &  Smolensky  1993,  Stiebels
line=543 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,83.42,336.14,97.4 iscore=0.17                     :2000a,b; see Aissen 1999 for a different account).

