line=607 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,321.86,538.61,335.84 iscore=0.06                                                                                 :We  have just seen that the format of generalized case allows to account for the factor
line=608 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,305.78,538.64,319.76 iscore=0.19                                                                                 :salience by means of split case. It can also account for the factor semantic role, this
line=609 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,289.64,538.55,303.62 iscore=0.38                                                                                 :time by the use of lexical marking. Lexical case can indicate a semantic role that de-
line=610 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,273.56,538.65,287.54 iscore=0.19                                                                                 :viates from the prototypical role properties associated with positions in the argument
line=611 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,257.48,538.63,271.46 iscore=0.25                                                                                 :hierarchy. Recall that in prototypical transitive verbs, the higher argument ([+lr]) is
line=612 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,241.4,538.69,255.38 iscore=0.07                                                                                  :an agent (a controller entity), while the lower argument ([+hr]) is a patient (an af-
line=613 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,225.26,538.59,239.24 iscore=0.27                                                                                 :fected entity). If these two features are lexically assigned to the ‘wrong’ role, they
line=614 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,209.18,538.63,223.16 iscore=0.21                                                                                 :invite a different reading: [+lr] for the lowest argument invites the controller (or
line=615 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,193.1,538.65,207.08 iscore=0.38                                                                                  :agentive) reading, whereas [+hr] for the highest argument invites the affectedness (or
line=616 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,176.96,175.56,190.94 iscore=0.08                                                                                 :experiencer) reading.
line=617 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=73.68,160.16,538.69,174.14 iscore=0.00                                                                                :   (31) illustrates this with some examples from German   and  one example  from
line=618 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,143.18,538.62,157.16 iscore=0.29                                                                                 :Hindi. In (31a) the lower argument is exceptionally marked with [+lr], while in (31b)
line=619 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,126.14,538.62,140.12 iscore=0.07                                                                                 :the higher argument is exceptionally marked with [+hr]. Together with the respective
line=620 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,109.15,538.6,123.14 iscore=0.07                                                                                  :default features, a constellation results in which dative is the optimal case. The DAT-
line=621 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,92.18,538.65,106.16 iscore=0.25                                                                                  :marking on the helpee in (31a) invites the reading that this is an argument with agent
line=622 fonts=F1-14.0 bbox=56.7,75.13,538.64,89.12 iscore=0.25                                                                                   :properties, while the DAT-marking in (31b) invites the reading of being affected, that

